There are only 23 diamonds with a .99 carat, and 1558 with 1.00 carat.
The definition of a carat is its weight, so perhaps diamonds are selected to be a certain weight after cutting.

diamonds |>

  ggplot(aes(x = carat)) +

  geom_text(
    stat = "bin",
    aes(label = after_stat(count)),

  )

na.rm = TRUE makes sure that the operation succeeds for mean and sum

flights |> 
  summarise(
    mean = mean(dep_time),
    sum = sum(dep_time)
  )
## # A tibble: 1 Ã— 2
##    mean   sum
##   <dbl> <int>
## 1    NA    NA

  summarise(
    mean = mean(dep_time, na.rm = TRUE),
    sum = sum(dep_time, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
## # A tibble: 1 Ã— 2

nycflights13::flights |> 
  mutate(
    cancelled = is.na(dep_time),
    sched_hour = sched_dep_time %/% 100,
    sched_min = sched_dep_time %% 100,
    sched_dep_time = sched_hour + (sched_min / 60)
  ) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = sched_dep_time)) + 
  geom_freqpoly(aes(color = cancelled), binwidth = 1/4) +
  facet_wrap(~ cancelled, scales = "free_y")

From ?geom_violin: A violin plot is a compact display of a continuous distribution. It is a blend of geom_boxplot() and geom_density(): a violin plot is a mirrored density plot displayed in the same way as a boxplot.

geom_quasirandom avoids overlapping by using a van der Corput sequence or Tukeys texturing. geom_beeswarm does point-size based offset.

  group_by(cut) |> 
  mutate(freq_cut = n / sum(n)) |>

11.5.3.1

cut_width sets the bin width to a specific number, cut_number divides the data into a specific number of bins.

diamonds |> 
  filter(carat < 3) |> 
  ggplot(
    aes(
    x = carat, 
    color = cut_width(price, 5000)
    )
  ) +
  geom_freqpoly()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

The prices follows the carat (weight), which is as I expect based on our other analysis.

diamonds |> 
  filter(carat < 3) |> 
  ggplot(
    aes(
      x = cut_width(carat, 0.5),
      y = price
    )
  ) +
  geom_boxplot()

Plotting of individual values is better for picking out outliers, because they are empasized against the majority of cases that correlate. A binned summary graph would not show outliers as clearly, if at all.

diamonds |> 
  filter(x >= 4) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point() +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(4, 11), ylim = c(4, 11))

As can be seen in this graph, by enforcing a certain number of observations we better understand the underlying data:

diamonds |> 
  filter(x >= 4) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = carat, y = price)) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(group = cut_number(carat, 20)))
